The paper discusses a stress monitoring system that uses physiological samples to derive personalized stress prediction models. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category, as it deals with the interaction between humans and technology. Additionally, the paper proposes a calibration technique that improves the accuracy of generic stress prediction models, which involves machine learning (cs.LG) and cybernetics (cs.CY). The paper also discusses the merits and limitations of the proposed stress monitoring system, which suggests that it may belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. Finally, the paper validates its approach on stress datasets, which suggests that it may belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
